STEP 1: Understand the Dataset
            Your Excel file has 7 key sheets (tables), typically:
            
            Sales_Data ‚Äì Fact table (contains Sales Amount, Quantity, Order Date, ProductKey, etc.)
            SalesOrder_Data ‚Äì Order-level details (Order ID, CustomerKey, etc.)
            Customer_Data ‚Äì Customer demographics (name, gender, age, income, etc.)
            Product_Data ‚Äì Product details (category, subcategory, price, cost, etc.)
            Reseller_Data ‚Äì Reseller information (for B2B sales)
            SalesTerritory_Data ‚Äì Region, Country, and Territory info
            Date_Data ‚Äì Calendar table (date, month, quarter, year)

            A Fact table stores the measurable, quantitative data.
            for example: sales, revenue, profit, quantity, discount, etc.

üü© Goal: Build a star schema ‚Üí Sales_Data is the central fact table, all others are dimension tables.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
            In Customer_Data and Reseller_Data, the first row often has:
            
            | CustomerKey | CustomerName | ... |
            |--------------|---------------|
            | -1 | Not Applicable | ... |
            
            üí° Meaning:
            -1 is a placeholder (dummy key) used when a sale record in the fact table (Sales_Data) doesn‚Äôt have a matching customer or reseller.
            Instead of leaving it blank or NULL, data engineers use -1 to maintain referential integrity between fact and dimension tables.
            
            Referential integrity ensures that relationships between tables remain valid and consistent.
            In simple terms:
            Every value in a foreign key column (in a fact table) must exist as a corresponding primary key in its related dimension table.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 2: Data Cleaning
            In Power Query (Transform Data):
            ‚úÖ Remove duplicates (especially in Customer or Product tables)
            ‚úÖ Ensure correct data types:
            Date columns ‚Üí Date
            Price, Sales, Profit ‚Üí Decimal Number
            Keys ‚Üí Whole Number
            ‚úÖ Rename columns clearly (e.g., Product_Name, Customer_ID)
            ‚úÖ Handle nulls ‚Äî replace with ‚ÄúUnknown‚Äù or 0 as needed
            ‚úÖ Ensure consistent date formats (e.g., M/d/yyyy)
            ‚úÖ Format currencies ‚Üí USD (or your local currency)

STEP 3: Data Modeling (Relationships)
            In Model view:
            
            Relationship	Type
            Sales_Data[CustomerKey] ‚Üí Customer_Data[CustomerKey]	Many-to-One
            Sales_Data[ProductKey] ‚Üí Product_Data[ProductKey]	Many-to-One
            Sales_Data[ResellerKey] ‚Üí Reseller_Data[ResellerKey]	Many-to-One
            Sales_Data[SalesTerritoryKey] ‚Üí SalesTerritory_Data[SalesTerritoryKey]	Many-to-One
            Sales_Data[OrderDateKey] ‚Üí Date_Data[DateKey]	Many-to-One

‚û°Ô∏è Star Schema: One fact table (Sales) surrounded by lookup tables.

STEP 4: DAX Measures
            Here are key DAX formulas to create:
            Measure	Formula
            | Measure                  | Formula                                                             |
            | ------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
            | **Total Sales**          | `SUM(Sales_Data[SalesAmount])`                                      |
            | **Total Orders**         | `DISTINCTCOUNT(Sales_Data[SalesOrderNumber])`                       |
            | **Total Quantity**       | `SUM(Sales_Data[OrderQuantity])`                                    |
            | **Total Profit**         | `SUMX(Sales_Data, Sales_Data[SalesAmount] - Sales_Data[TotalCost])` |
            | **Profit Margin %**      | `DIVIDE([Total Profit], [Total Sales])`                             |
            | **Average Order Value**  | `DIVIDE([Total Sales], [Total Orders])`                             |
            | **Sales LY (Last Year)** | `CALCULATE([Total Sales], SAMEPERIODLASTYEAR(Date_Data[FullDate]))` |
            | **YoY Growth %**         | `DIVIDE([Total Sales] - [Sales LY], [Sales LY])`                    |

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Dashboard Design
Page 1: Sales Overview
            KPI Cards: Total Sales, Total Profit, Profit Margin, YoY Growth %
            Line Chart: Sales over Time (Date_Data)
            Map: Sales by Country/Region
            Column Chart: Sales by Product Category
            Donut Chart: Sales by Customer Segment

Page 2: Product Insights
            Bar Chart: Top 10 Products by Sales
            Matrix: Category ‚Üí Subcategory ‚Üí Product (Sales, Profit)
            Scatter Plot: Profit vs. Quantity (colored by Category)

Page 3: Regional/Reseller Performance
            Map or Filled Map: Sales by Territory
            Clustered Column: Region vs. Total Sales
            Table: Reseller Name, Sales, Profit, Margin

Page 4: Customer Analysis
            Card: Total Customers
            Donut Chart: Sales by Gender or Occupation
            Line Chart: Customer Growth over Time

üí° STEP 6: Business Insights
            Once visuals are built, derive insights such as:
            üèÜ Top-performing category ‚Äì e.g., Bikes account for 45% of total revenue
            üìâ Low-margin products ‚Äì Accessories have 10% profit margin vs. 25% overall
            üåç Regional differences ‚Äì Europe sales growing faster than North America
            üïí Seasonal trends ‚Äì Sales spike during Q4 every year
            üí∞ High-value customers ‚Äì Top 5% customers contribute 40% of revenue


Task 1: Data Model Preparation
------------------------------------------
            Import all 7 sheets into Power BI (or Excel Power Pivot).
            Create relationships:
            Sales_data[SalesOrderLineKey] ‚Üí Sales Order_data[SalesOrderLineKey]
            Sales_data[SalesTerritoryKey] ‚Üí Sales Territory_data[SalesTerritoryKey]
            Sales_data[ResellerKey] ‚Üí Reseller_data[ResellerKey]
            Sales_data[CustomerKey] ‚Üí Customer_data[CustomerKey]
            Sales_data[ProductKey] ‚Üí Product_data[ProductKey]
            Sales_data[OrderDateKey] ‚Üí Date_data[DateKey]
            
            Ensure one-to-many relationships (dimension ‚Üí fact).
            üìå Outcome: A star schema model ready for dashboarding.

Task 2: Sales Overview Dashboard
-------------------------------------------
            Objective: Show company-wide sales performance.
            Steps:
            Add a Card Visual ‚Üí Sales_data[Sales Amount] ‚Üí Total Sales.
            Add a Card Visual ‚Üí Sales_data[Order Quantity] ‚Üí Total Orders.
            
            Add a Line Chart:
            Axis ‚Üí Date_data[Full Date]
            Values ‚Üí Sales_data[Sales Amount]
            
            This shows daily/monthly sales trend.
            
            Add a Slicer ‚Üí Date_data[Year] and Date_data[Month] to filter.
            üìå Outcome: Management can track overall performance and time trends.

Task 3: Product Performance Dashboard
----------------------------------------------
              Objective: Identify best-selling products.
              Steps:
              Add a Clustered Bar Chart:
              
              Axis ‚Üí Product_data[Category]
              Values ‚Üí Sales_data[Sales Amount]
              
              Add a Matrix Table:
              Rows ‚Üí Product_data[Subcategory]
              Columns ‚Üí Product_data[Product]
              Values ‚Üí Sales_data[Sales Amount], Sales_data[Order Quantity]
              
              Add a Pie Chart ‚Üí Sales by Product_data[Color].
              
              üìå Outcome: Clear view of top products and categories driving revenue.

Task 4: Regional & Reseller Dashboard
---------------------------------------------------------
              Objective: See how sales vary across territories and partners.
              Steps:
              Add a Map Visual:
              
              Location ‚Üí Sales Territory_data[Country]
              Size ‚Üí Sales_data[Sales Amount]
              
              Add a Clustered Column Chart:
              Axis ‚Üí Sales Territory_data[Region]
              Values ‚Üí Sales_data[Sales Amount]
              
              Add a Table:
              Rows ‚Üí Reseller_data[Reseller]
              Values ‚Üí Sales_data[Sales Amount], Sales_data[Order Quantity]
              Sort descending by Sales Amount.
              
              üìå Outcome: Easy tracking of which regions and resellers are strong or weak.

Task 5: Customer Insights Dashboard
---------------------------------------------
              Objective: Focus on customer behavior.
              Steps:
              Add a Table:
              Rows ‚Üí Customer_data[Customer]
              Values ‚Üí Sales_data[Sales Amount]
              Sort by Sales Amount (Top Customers).
              
              Add a Donut Chart:
              Legend ‚Üí Customer_data[Country-Region]
              Values ‚Üí Sales_data[Sales Amount]
              
              Add a Card ‚Üí Distinct Count of Customer_data[CustomerKey].
              
              üìå Outcome: Helps understand top customers and geographic spread.

Task 6: Interactive Filtering
----------------------------------------------
              Add Slicers for:
              Year / Quarter (Date_data)
              Product Category (Product_data)
              Region (Sales Territory_data)
              Reseller (Reseller_data)
              
              This allows managers to slice dashboards quickly.
              üìå Outcome: Fully interactive dashboard for analysis.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Dashboard Design
Page 1: Sales Overview - Executive Summary
KPIs: Total Sales, Profit, Profit Margin %, Order Count

Charts:
Sales & Profit Trend (Line chart by Month)
Sales by Region (Map or Bar Chart)
Top 5 Products by Revenue (Bar Chart)
Sales by Channel (Pie/Donut Chart)

Page 2: Product Performance
Table or Matrix:
Product Category, Subcategory, Total Sales, Profit, Margin
Visuals:
Clustered bar: ‚ÄúSales by Product Category‚Äù
Scatter: ‚ÄúProfit vs Sales by Product‚Äù

Page 3: Regional Analysis
Map: Sales by Country/City
Column chart: Sales by Region and Year
KPI Card: Top-performing region

Page 4: Customer Insights
Table: Top 10 Customers by Revenue
Funnel: Sales pipeline by stage (if available)
KPI: Repeat Customers (%)

| Metric           | Formula (DAX)                           | Description              |
| ---------------- | --------------------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| Total Sales      | `SUM(Sales[SalesAmount])`               | Total revenue            |
| Total Cost       | `SUM(Sales[TotalProductCost])`          | Total cost of goods sold |
| Total Profit     | `[Total Sales] - [Total Cost]`          | Profit                   |
| Profit Margin %  | `DIVIDE([Total Profit], [Total Sales])` | Profit percentage        |
| Order Count      | `COUNTROWS(Sales)`                      | Number of orders         |
| Avg. Order Value | `DIVIDE([Total Sales], [Order Count])`  | Average order revenue    |



